{"source_key":"sha256-f6bbf31bf9e6709157d23bb2425b0d13","record_index":2963,"record_hash":"sha256:e958b7d72dde2892db58fe5b3e3a105a71dec7ce1a0355d92d77c9d5fb96aa8e","timestamp":"2026-06-03T13:35:49.896Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yes, for the plain-branch read path.\n\nIn [workspace.rs]([REDACTED:path]), `head_info(ctx)` calls `but_workspace::head_info()` unless we’re specifically in edit mode. That uses `Graph::from_head`, so it works from whatever `HEAD` is, including a normal checked-out branch.\n\nThe no-workspace behavior is:\n\n- `workspace_metadata()` returns `None`.\n- `head_info` still returns a stack-like projection for the checked-out branch.\n- We strip `StackId::single_branch_id()` so the returned `HeadInfoStack.id` becomes `None`, because that id is synthetic/volatile.\n- Branch data still exists: name, ref, tip, base, commits, push status.\n\nSo `applied_stacks(ctx)` and `applied_stack(ctx, None)` should work in normal Git mode. `applied_stack(ctx, Some(stack_id))` generally should not, because plain branch mode doesn’t have a durable stack id. That’s fine; callers in normal Git mode should resolve by branch/ref, not stack id.\n\nThis is also why the review fix to search all stacks by branch name when `stack_id == None` was the right move.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-06-03T13:35:49.896Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}